text: So I moved to London because my partner is studying at University of College London. He is working on getting his PhD in Cognitive neuroscience. And we decided that it would be fun if I moved here as well. So, I came from the United States and I have been living here now since the 29 January 2019, so almost full year. um, it's been a very exciting journey. um, it took me approximately eight or nine months to be able to make the move happen. um, I worked as a nurse back home, um, for almost two years. And I had to go through an entire process to get my nursing license and my visa in order. And now I work here, um, in reading as a nurse. I work on a diabetes rheumatology ward, which, um, is very different than the nursing I used to do. I was previously a nurse in the intensive care unit and often worked with patients after cardiac surgeries, um, ear, nose and throat surgeries, as well as various medical conditions like respiratory failure. And now I'm dealing primarily with medical patients who are generally not as sick. And, um, my patient workload is much larger as well. I was previously only working with two to three patients, and now I work with an average of eight to ten patients, which is quite a large difference. um, so it was a very large adjustment period when I first came here. I had to adjust, first of all, just to having more patients. um, so there's a lot of prioritization and, uh, delegation that I needed to quickly learn in order to be efficient and practice safe, uh, nursing care. um, but luckily, I have been working with a great team, and the team that I work with are from several different countries. The NHS is currently having a massive nursing shortage, so they often bring in nurses from the EU as well as other countries. The agency I went through is, um, actually based in the Philippines. And so there is a large Philippine population at our hospital, um, as well as people from Spain, Portugal, um, all over Africa and America, surprisingly, as I have yet to meet another American nurse. um, but that's all right. ah, so it's been, it's been fun getting to know everyone from all these different countries and to have people with sort of a similar experience. So, um, that definitely helped with my transition period. um, and now they are great friends. But luckily I got a little better with some fluids and IV antibiotics. um, but it was very, um, interesting because I had never even seen my vp yet. Let alone go to ame. So I was messaging all of my coworkers, all my friends, trying to figure out what to do. And they were a great support system during that time, which was really nice.
